Denote by (\mathbf{V}) the volume of a parallelepiped determined by vectors \mathbf{a}, \mathbf{b}, and \mathbf{c}. Then \mathbf{V} = | \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) |, where \mathbf{\cdot} is the dot product, \mathbf{x} \times \mathbf{y} is the cross product, and |\mathbf{z}| is the magnitude of vector \mathbf{z}. The formula for finding the volume of a parallelepiped in terms of the magnitudes and angles of its vectors is \mathbf{V} = \frac{1}{2} |\mathbf{a}| |\mathbf{b}| |\mathbf{c}| sin (\theta_{ab}) + |\mathbf{b}| |\mathbf{c}| sin (\theta_{bc}) + |\mathbf{a}| |\mathbf{c}| sin (\theta_{ac}). Here \theta_{xy} denotes the angle between vectors \mathbf{x} and \mathbf{y}.\rightharpoondown</think>
\begin{align*}
